communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The cause of the illness is not yet elucidated nor has whether illnesses outside western New York State have occurred. It would be useful to know what the time interval was between ingestion of the beans and the onset of symptoms, whether fever was present and how long the illness lasted. A small cluster of gastroenteritis associated with refried beans in 2005 in Minnesota was caused by _Clostridium perfringens_ (http://www.outbreakdatabase.com/details/refried-beans-2005/) and another was caused by the same toxin producing organism in Nevada in 2009 (http://outbreakdatabase.com/details/nevada-restaurant-refried-beans-2009/). This toxin induced illness, however, generally causes diarrhea rather than vomiting which is more characteristic of staphylococcal food poisoning.

Refried beans (Spanish: frijoles refritos) (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Refried_beans) is a dish of cooked and mashed beans and is a traditional staple of Mexican and Tex-Mex cuisine, although each cuisine has a different approach when making the dish. Refried beans are also popular in many other Latin American countries. The name is a direct calque (literal, word-for-word, or root-for-root translation) of Spanish frijoles refritos, refritos meaning "well-fried", and not "fried again" as might be assumed from the use of re- in English. The prefix re- could be used as an intensifier in Latin, as evident in e.g. resplendent, a meaning that has been inherited by Spanish alongside the commoner meaning indicating repetition. In this dish, after being boiled and then mashed into a paste, the beans are sometimes then fried or baked, though usually neither, thus making the term "refried" even more misleading. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4561982,234.]
